{"cursor":"8641","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nThe 'signature' of a metric tensor (or more generally a symmetric bilinear form,\nthought of as a quadratic form) is the number of positive, negative and zero\neigenvalues of the metric. That is, the corresponding real symmetric matrix is\ndiagonalised, and the diagonal entries of each sign counted. If the matrix of\nthe metric tensor is , then the number of positive, negative and zero\neigenvalues p, q and r may take values from 0 to n with . The signature may be\ndenoted by a pair of integers implying , a triple , or as an explicit list such\nas or , in this case resp. . Rowland, Todd. \"Matrix Signature.\" From MathWorld--\nA Wolfram Web Resource, created by Eric W. Weisstein.\nhttp://mathworld.wolfram.com/MatrixSignature.html \n\nThe signature is said to be 'indefinite' or 'mixed' if both p and q are nonzero,\nand degenerate if r is nonzero. A Riemannian metric is a metric with a\n(positive) definite signature. A Lorentzian metric is one with signature , or .\n\nThere is another definition of 'signature' of a nondegenerate metric tensor\ngiven by a single number s defined as , where p and q are as above. For example,\nfor and for .\n","linknr":201,"url":"metric_signature","recorded":1376426762,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Metric_signature&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Metric_signature&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metric_signature","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=f